<br>
Now imagine this situation : I cast snare, fear animal, Dot, and then invis vs animal.<br>
<br>
Now my questions :<br>
- in the situations above, if an other griff (not the one I am attacking) goes near me, will he see me ?<br>
- if the griff I am attacking run into an other griff, will this add griff attack me too ?<br>
<br>
So my questions : if we have attacked an animal, is it useful to cast invis vs animals so the other ones will not attack us ?<br>
<br>
Thanks<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
Talaever, Druid of the 10th season, Mithaniel Marr <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udaeddwin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Daeddwin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/12/01 8:33:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovespells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2320.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Using invis vs animal to kite ?</span><hr size=1> The way I understand it, is that invisibility of any kind will not hide you from an old-world monster you've aggroed.  Not sure about Kunark, since monsters there will give up the chase if you get far enough away.  So this is how I see your situation happening.<br>
<br>
Snare/Fear/DoT Griffawn<br>
<br>
Invis to Animals yourself<br>
<br>
Griffawn meets a friend<br>
<br>
Fear breaks, Griffawn and friend return<br>
<br>
First Griffawn attacks you, breaking invis<br>
<br>
Two Griffawns on you<br>
<br>
In short, I don't think it'd work very well.  Personally, I think ivisibility is kindof broken that way, but I can understand that it'd be a little too unbalancing otherwise.<br>
<br>
When it comes to Griffawns, I'd just use Root/DoT or blast kiting.  I killed most of my Griffs in North Karana, and there are huge areas near the Southern zone border along the river where there are very few roamers.  I'd just pull your Griffawn down in that direction to kill it.  I saw very few adds, but if they happen, you can just run to the bridge guards.  (A failed kill is a better situation than lost xp.)<br>
<br>
If you really feel like taking chances, and have plenty of mana you can try fearing the additional griffawn as well.  Panic Animal is fairly cheap, but it has a fairly short duration.<br>
<br>
 <p>Daeddwin Proudfoot<br>
32nd (FINALLY) Level Lowbie Halfling Druid<br>
Officer of <i>Spirit of Norrath</i><br>
<b>Lanys T'yvl</b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/upatofnaud.showPublicProfile?language=EN>patofnaud</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/12/01 9:04:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovespells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2320.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Using invis vs animal to kite ?</span><hr size=1> Couple of points from a Griff killer.. (Note the surname)<br>
<br>
At 10, I wouldn't worry about hunting Griffs in NK yet.. ;)<br>
<br>
At around 19-20 Griffawns will start to be obtainable. Trick is to snare them, then run them down to the waters edge and root them. Then DoT and med. That way you wont get any uninvited guests. If you snare does not hold, high tail it toward a zone, once you get far enough ahead that you can barely hear them, stop (without turning around) and cast Careless Lightning on them. Once you do that a couple times, and take some wind out of their sails, retry snare. Do NOT melee them. The freekin hurt big time.<br>
<br>
At around 23, Griffennes will become fair game and Griffawns will green out. Once the Griffawns green out, they also start to become INDIFF for some reason. This makes it a bit easier no run around tracking Griffennes.<br>
<br>
At 24 you get wolfform, this makes running aroun the zone ever easier as only things that will aggro you will be Griffens, Griffennes, Hill Giants and Grimfeather.<br>
<br>
Word to the wise, if you see Grimfeather on track, TRACK HIM. Not so you can engage him, but so you know what direction NOT to go in! He WILL kill you so fast you will think you accidently zoned. <p><body lang=EN-US style='tab-interval:.5in'>

