<P>Patofwaan Griffonbate<br>
25th Season Friend Of Wolves <br><br> <span style='color:lime'>Proud members of <a href="http://www.geocities.com/karmaofmorellthule">Karma</a> Guild, In the Land of Morell-Thule<br>
<img src=http://www.ultranet.com/~patnod/testsig.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udaeddwin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Daeddwin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/12/01 10:47:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovespells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2320.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Using invis vs animal to kite ?</span><hr size=1> I have to disagree a little, Patofwaan.<br>
<br>
While 10 is a bit early to be conteplating Griffawns, I killed my first at level 16.  I'll grant that I was root/DoTting and did so near a zone border, but I would say that Griffawns are good hunting from 17 up.  Kiting them with Ignite takes a little longer, yes... but I know it's possible, because that's what I did.<br>
<br>
The only trick is the re-snare.  Often I had to re-snare a 'fawn to continue my kite.  If I flubbed up the re-snare, then there would be trouble.  Basically, Ijust ran twice as far as I would if I was going to blast, and try to throw a snare on it.  With the new root/DoT changes, I'd probably try to root it, then re-Snare.<br>
<br>
At 19, Griffawns were starting to thin out xp-wise... at least that's the way it seemed to me.  17 and 18 were my prime 'fawn killing days.<br>
<br>
 <p>Daeddwin Proudfoot<br>
32nd (FINALLY) Level Lowbie Halfling Druid<br>
Officer of <i>Spirit of Norrath</i><br>
<b>Lanys T'yvl</b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ufoofur1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Foofur1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/12/01 10:55:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovespells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2320.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Using invis vs animal to kite ?</span><hr size=1> I killed my first at fawn at 14 but I only killed the blue conning ones using root-DOT/rotting method.  I would advise sticking to blue cons using this method because grasping roots has a higher resist rate.  I found that straight up kiting (snare-dot-nuke) I would not have enough mana to kill one if I got a couple resists but with the rotting method I have between 2 to 3 bubs of mana after the fight so I don't have long to med for next fight.<br>
<br>
Laters,<br>
Foofur <br>
15th season Druid of the Vale <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=drew>Drew</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/12/01 12:11:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovespells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2320.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Effects of invis</span><hr size=1> <br>
   Invisibility, in EQ, essentially just makes mobs that can't see invis con indifferent to you, rather than whatever they would normally con.  (Yes, it lowers high faction as well as raising low faction.)  <br>
<br>
   So, imagine that those griffs conned indifferent to you normally, or try attacking some mobs that are indifferent (or better; say bears).  Would that faction keep a feared one from coming back to you and attacking, once you started the combat?  No.  When the feared one meets another, and they exchange hate lists, would that faction mean the second won't come attack you to help out the first?  No.<br>
<br>
   Invis is a travel spell, a preventative measure.  Once you're in combat, the mobs you've aggroed can always see you.  That includes ones that they drag into the combat by &quot;yelling for help&quot; to the mobs around them.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/12/01 2:09:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovespells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2320.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Effects of invis</span><hr size=1> It all depends on whether the mobs swap aggro lists.  I pull mobs in Kunark all the time, including dragons, while having superior camo up because I am high enough in level that I don't passed to other mob's aggro lists in most cases.    Superior Camo allows me to pull the mob I want (which ignores the camo, of course) while not worrying about adds.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uflaim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Flaim</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/12/01 2:24:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovespells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2320.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Effects of invis</span><hr size=1> Camo and the hate list is a funky thing in Vellious.<br>
<br>
If you agro, let say Ry'Gorr orc Centurion.  You run out of it's &quot;chase you&quot; distance.  You camo up.  You should still be on the Cent's hate list and are of course.  But now other orcs, Scouts for instance, that previously were indifferent you, now hate you and see you.  Even though they you never agroed the Scout, nor the Cent was anywhere near him.<br>
<br>
Same with the Wurms in GD, agro a baby, get away.  Baby Wurm stops following you.  Camo up, go to the caves,,,Wham &quot;You Appear&quot;, a Elder Guardian Wurm hits you, blah, blah, blah.<br>
<br>
Not everytime, but it happens.  <br>
<br>
Mix it up with group members, and it spreads like a disease, camoed or not.  And the only cure I have found is zoning.<br>
<br>
